        <title>So who has dyslexia?</title>
        <contents>&lt;p&gt;The prevalence of dyslexia is unknown; with estimations varying greatly between 1% to 33% of the population. In the UK, it's thought that one in ten people has dyslexia.Â Internationally, there are differing definitions of dyslexia, but despite the significant differences between the writing systems, Italian, German and English speaking populations suffer similarly from dyslexia.&lt;sup id="cite_ref-90" class="reference"&gt;&lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dyslexia#cite_note-90"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;Â Dyslexia is not limited to difficulty in converting letters into sounds, but Chinese dyslexics have difficulty in extracting shapes ofÂ &lt;span class="nolink"&gt;Chinese charactersÂ i&lt;/span&gt;nto meanings. (&lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dyslexia#Genetics"&gt;wikipedia&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;sup id="cite_ref-91" class="reference"&gt;&lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dyslexia#cite_note-91"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;The exact cause of dyslexia is unknown, but it's generally accepted to be passed on through families.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;However, when dealing with children with dyslexia it's vital to emphasise that the condition doesn't have to hold them back: Einstein, Thomas Edison, RIchard Branson, Orlando Bloom, Darcy Bussell, Tom Cruise, Bill Gates and Steve Jobs, Keira Knightley and &lt;a href="http://www.bdadyslexia.org.uk/about-dyslexia/famous-dyslexics.html"&gt;oh so many more&lt;/a&gt;Â have overcome the obstacle and gone on to great things. Your students can too:-)Â Here's a good video by the British Dyslexia association:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://youtu.be/l_qGJ9svUbM"&gt;http://youtu.be/l_qGJ9svUbM&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</contents>
