        <title>Strategies (2)</title>
        <contents>&lt;p&gt;In this &lt;a href="http://www.theguardian.com/teacher-network/teacher-blog/2013/sep/09/supporting-students-with-dyslexia-teachers-tips-pupils"&gt;article from the UK GuardianTeacher network&lt;/a&gt;, David Imrie shares tips on how to present work for dyslexic students.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/Older%20Scrabble%20Dutch%20edition%20letter%20overview.jpg" width="400" height="300" alt="scrabble" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Amongst his suggestions are:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Layout: ensure worksheets only contain the necessary information and no extraneous detail which would overburden a student struggling to take it all in&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Illustrations - where possible include graphics with text so students can visualise without having to understand every word&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Fonts and background colours Â -some are more easily viewed by dyslexic students than others.Â Â Teachers can download free specialist fonts, such asÂ &lt;a href="http://opendyslexic.org/"&gt;OpenDyslexic&lt;/a&gt;, which are free and can run on Microsoft software. Students who find characters invert or "swim" benefit from this font. Blue and yellow go well together, or a green background, or glasses with a particular filter or tint. More on &lt;a href="http://www.bdadyslexia.org.uk/about-dyslexia/further-information/eyes-and-dyslexia.html"&gt;visual stress from the BDA here&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;</contents>
